One way to reduce the number of possible paths is to reduce the number of distinct cases, often via refactoring or a simpler yet more general algorithm; to use an extremely contrived example, it&#x27;s like the difference between<p><pre><code>    int addOne(int x) {
      if(x == 0)
        return 1;
      else if(x == 1)
        return 2;
      ...
    }
</code></pre>
and<p><pre><code>    int addOne(int x) {
      return x + 1;
    }

</code></pre>
I always keep in mind the famous Dijkstra quotes about testing and program complexity:<p>&quot;Program testing can be used to show the presence of bugs, but never to show their absence!&quot;<p>&quot;Simplicity is prerequisite for reliability.&quot;
